Let’s talk about the elephant in the room 🐘 Everyone is telling you NOT to work for exposure, so when IS it OK to work for free?

From my experience, clients that YOU approach and volunteer to do a quick job for in exchange for strong testimonials are a great way to elevate your credentials on your website and social media. If you do this once or twice to beef up your portfolio, there is so much to gain when future clients are considering you.

Another way to use your time for free is to gain knowledge. When I was first starting out I volunteered at events in my industry (setting up chairs, greeting guests, introducing panelists) to meet a lot of pros in the field, ask questions, and exchange contact info. So it’s not always about doing big projects. Get yourself in the middle of an event, or wherever the pros or ideal clients hang out, to form strong connections.

However you devote your time without compensation should be chosen wisely––make sure it’s totally worthwhile and you have a lot to gain for your personal growth!

We’ve all been there –– We work with a client on a logo. They love it. They sign off on it. We’re all excited and celebrate. And a month later their website launches under a TOTALLY NEW AND UNEXPECTED DIY butchered version of their logo.

Let’s address two issues here: Why is this happening to so many designers and how do we prevent it?

A logo is just a design for a business name if it doesn’t have extensive brand research backing it. When I first started out, I offered logo design as a standalone service. Clients loved the design, and before I knew it, they took their brand in a totally different direction, and my logo design was not needed anymore. Logo design does not solve a problem for a client other than just being a design; something cute and pretty. The real problem we want to address is:

❓WHO is this logo supposed to resonate with/who is the target customer?
❓WHAT does this business stand for?
❓WHY does this business exist and what is the mission?
❓HOW is this brand positioning itself so that it reaches the right customers?
❓WHERE is this brand going to market to be recognized by customers who need this product?
❓WHEN is this brand launching and does it align with customer needs?

Without proper research and focus on the ideal customer and what the brand stands for, a logo has no value or power. A logo WITH branding and research is complete; offering solutions, guiding your client to answers, and giving the client clarity on who they are, what their business stands for, and why they exist for the customer.

Designers, if you want your clients to truly value your work and get the most out of it, make sure you provide them with SOLUTIONS, not designs.

I finally got clarity on my brand a few years ago (when I experienced my own rebrand) and realized my mission is to help women run a business with fulfillment and joy. I’m not just helping brands grow, but I’m helping the entrepreneurs behind them love waking up every day to continue to help others. My “why” is to generate a ripple effect of impact. My webinars, business coaching, branding packages, courses, masterminds...all stem from that.

How can you do the same? Try to be more intentional in creating branches from your roots. Get clarity on why and who and get your roots nice and firm now.

Why is this all important? You become memorable, and people know why they need you.

How much do you really value your time and yourself? Enough to properly price your worth?

These are my 3 MVP (Mindset, Value, Pricing) Tips to set the foundation for pricing and charging what you’re worth.

It’s not always easy to come up with the right numbers, so hang on to these tips, and each time you price your service or product, ask yourself:

✨M – MINDSET: Is my money mindset in-check and healthy?

Keep track of what you earn and spend, appreciate money, become grateful for it, understand that there is no limit to what you can achieve, and that you deserve to have lots of money and prosper. You get to a healthy, comfortable place with money when you exercise your money mindset (tip: add some money mindset affirmations to your vision board). It doesn’t get awkward to expect it when you know that you are worthy of it.

✨V – VALUE: Am I making it clear to customers what the value of my offer is?

Do your customers really know what they’re getting in exchange for your service or product in addition to that item itself? Do you offer a confidence boost? Luxury quality? Convenience? What transformation do you offer your customer? What pain or stress are you relieving them from? Make sure that you can answer all of these questions. (My Brand With Intention Workbook helps answer these if you’re feeling stuck.)

✨P – PRICING: How does my gut feel about the numbers I’ve set?

If you have absolutely no idea what to charge, start at $25/hr. Think about how long it takes you to work. Do the math: 25 x # of hours = $___. Does that feel good and meet your financial goals? If not, try $35/hr, and keep going higher until everything feels aligned; your gut feeling, the numbers, the effort you put in, and the value you offer.

Once I start here, my self-worth gets a boost. How about you? Are you an MVP of self-worth? 🙂

They send me fancy-pants copy for their ads and websites, loaded with more jargon than you’d find in a dictionary. Then, they ask for amazing designs, hoping it’ll magically boost sales.

try this: “Get the best night’s sleep without the sweat and all the comfort in these cool-to-the-touch high quality silk pajamas! Feel refreshed and stylish!”

☝🏻Notice how the second example is solving a problem while the first one is just a fluffy metaphor that doesn’t help anyone with anything.
